:[{"name":"Ryche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire):","from Middle English <i>wich</i>, a variant of <i>wik</i>, the commonest sense of which was ‘dairy farm’, probably an occupational name for someone who worked at a <i>wich</i>, or a habitational name from any of the places so called. See   Wick  .","topographic name from Middle English <i>wiche</i> ‘wych elm’, for someone who lived by an elm tree."],"variants":[{"name":"Wick","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>wik(e)</i> (Old English <i>wīc</i>) ‘building; enclosed piece of land; dependent farm where a certain kind of work is done’. In placenames the term is frequently combined with words associated with food production, as in Butterwick ‘butter wick’, Chiswick ‘cheese wick’, Cowick ‘cow wick’, Hardwick ‘herd wick’, Gatwick ‘goat wick’, Shapwick ‘sheep wick’, Goswick ‘goose wick’, Berwick ‘barley wick’, Fishwick ‘fish wick’. The most common sense is ‘dairy farm’. The surname may be topographic or occupational, denoting someone who lived or worked at a <i>wick</i> (compare   Wicker  ), or habitational, denoting someone who lived at or came from a place called Wick (of which there are examples in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Somerset, Wiltshire, and Worcestershire), Wyke (Devon, Dorset, Surrey, Yorkshire), or Week (Cornwall, Devon, Hampshire, Isle of Wight, Somerset).","German: from a medieval personal name <i>Wicko</i>, a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names formed with the element <i>wīg</i> ‘battle, war’.","German: habitational name from Wick (Westphalia) or any of the places called Wieck or Wiek."]},{"name":"Weech","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Wyche  .","German: nickname for a beautiful person, from Middle High German <i>wæhe</i> ‘beautiful, precious’."]},{"name":"Wice","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Wyche  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Ryche was born about 1358, in Stepney, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Sir William Marrow II."},"et":{"about 1358–":"umbes 1358–Surnud","1354–1450":"1354–1450","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1358–Female":"1358–Surnud","1358":"1358","about 1358":"umbes 1358","1354":"1354","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Stepney,Middlesex,England.":"Stepney, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1358–":"noin 1358–Kuollut","1354–1450":"1354–1450","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1358–Female":"1358–Kuollut","1358":"1358","about 1358":"noin 1358","1354":"1354","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Stepney,Middlesex,England.":"Stepney, Middlesex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1358–":"environ 1358–Décédée","1354–1450":"1354–1450","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1358–Female":"1358–Décédée","1358":"1358","about 1358":"environ 1358","1354":"1354","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","London, Middlesex, England":"Londres, Middlesex, Angleterre","Stepney,Middlesex,England.":"Stepney, Middlesex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Margaret Ryche est née environ 1358, à Stepney, Middlesex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Sir William Marrow II."},"de":{"about 1358–":"um 1358–Verstorben","1354–1450":"1354–1450","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1358–Female":"1358–Verstorben","1358":"1358","about 1358":"um 1358","1354":"1354","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Stepney,Middlesex,England.":"Stepney, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Margaret Ryche wurde um 1358 in Stepne